nd 320 tanks out of 400 to these Anti-Tank Squadrons.\n\nWhen the Egyptian Infantry started controlling hardpoints and fortresses along the Bar Lev line through a series of battles. On October 7th, Egyptian Armored units of the 2nd & 3rd Armies and Port Said Sector passed over the bridgeheads (Pontoon bridges) made by the Egyptian Combat Engineers and entered combat with the Infantry formations in several battles such as Battle of Firdan alongside the 2nd Infantry division and the heavy Armored battles of El Qantarah alongside the 18th Infantry division.\n\nThe Armored corps has done a lot of heroic actions throughout the war but their most notable action throughout the war was the advance of the 12th Brigade of the 4th Armored division 22 KM deep into Sinai without having Air or Artillery cover or even Anti-Tank support against a fully prepared Israeli force, although the Brigade wasn't supported very well so it managed to trick the Israelis and surprisingly attack them which led to heavy casualties on the Israeli side, however, the Israelis could defeat them at the end due to having Air, Artillery and Anti-Tank support.\n\n== Gulf War ==\nAs Iraq invaded Kuwait, Egypt alongside a group of Arab countries were extremely opposing Iraq after that. When the coalition was formed, Egypt established a 35,000 strong corps-sized force made up of the 4th Armored division, 3rd Mechanized division, 170th Airborne brigade, Special forces regiment and a number of support units such as Engineers and Air defence. \n\n\n\n[[Category:Military of Egypt]]\n", "name_user": "GELongstreet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEstablishment:linkfix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_Armored_Corps"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Fells", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name                = Tommy Fells\n| image               = Tom Fells.jpg\n| image_size          = 150\n| caption             = Fells while with [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in 1912.\n| fullname            = Thomas Fells\n| birth_date          = 8 January 1890\n| birth_place         = [[Rotherham]], England\n| death_date          = 1942 (aged 52)\n| death_place         = [[Lower Don Valley|Don Valley]], England\n| height              =  \n| position            = [[Full back (association football)|Full back]]\n| currentclub         =\n| youthyears1         =\n| youthclubs1         = \n| years1              = 1907\u20131911\n| clubs1              = [[Rotherham County F.C.|Rotherham County]]\n| caps1               = \n| years2              = 1911\u20131912\n| clubs2              = [[South Kirkby Colliery F.C.|South Kirkby]]\n| caps2               = \n| goals2              = \n| years3              = 1912\u20131914\n| clubs3              = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| caps3               = 15\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 1919\u20131920\n| clubs4              = [[South Kirkby Colliery F.C.|South Kirkby]]\n| caps4               =\n| goals4              =\n}}\n'''Thomas Fells''' was an English [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Full back (association football)|full back]] for [[South Kirkby Colliery F.C.|South Kirkby]], [[Rotherham County F.C.|Rotherham County]] and [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n\n==Playing career==\nFells began his football career with Rotherham County<ref>{{cite news|title=South Kirkby Player for Brentford|publisher=Sheffield Daily Telegraph|date=6 May 1912|page=1}}</ref> at least as early as 1907<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham County Versus Doncaster Rovers|publisher=Sheffield Daily Telegraph|date=27 December 1907|page=9}}</ref> who were regulars in the FA Cup at that time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham County Fined|publisher=Sheffield Daily Telegraph|date=23 March 1907|page=11}}</ref> He next joined South Kirkby<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=South Kirkby Colliery (Almost) Complete History|url=http://www.southkirkbycolliery.co.uk/player-a-z|publisher=Matthew Thomas|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> then joined Brentford in 1912.<ref>{{cite news|title=Football Fancies|publisher=Star Green 'Un|date=1 February 1913|page=1}}</ref> In the [[1912\u201313 Brentford F.C. season|1912-1913 season]] he made 8 appearances for Brentford and in the [[1913\u201314 Brentford F.C. season|1913-1914 season]] he made 7 appearances. In total he made 15 appearances for Brentford. After World War One, Tommy Fells is known to have returned to South Kirkby Colliery in 1919.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fells, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:South Kirkby Colliery F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham County F.C. players]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-defender-1890s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name                = Tommy Fells\n| image               = Tom Fells.jpg\n| image_size          = 150\n| caption             = Fells while with [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in 1912.\n| fullname            = Thomas Fells\n| birth_date          = 8 January 1890\n| birth_place         = [[Rotherham]], England\n| death_date          = 1942 (aged 52)\n| death_place         = [[Lower Don Valley|Don Valley]], England\n| height              =  \n| position            = [[Full back (association football)|Full back]]\n| currentclub         =\n| youthyears1         =\n| youthclubs1         = \n| years1              = 1907\u20131911\n| clubs1              = [[Rotherham County F.C.|Rotherham County]]\n| caps1               = \n| years2              = 1911\u20131912\n| clubs2              = [[South Kirkby Colliery F.C.|South Kirkby]]\n| caps2               = \n| goals2              = \n| years3              = 1912\u20131914\n| clubs3              = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| caps3               = 15\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 1919\u20131920\n| clubs4              = [[South Kirkby Colliery F.C.|South Kirkby]]\n| caps4               =\n| goals4              =\n}}\n'''Thomas Fells''' was an English [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Full back (association football)|full back]] for [[South Kirkby Colliery F.C.|South Kirkby]], [[Rotherham County F.C.|Rotherham County]] and [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n\n==Playing career==\nFells began his football career with Rotherham County<ref>{{cite news|title=South Kirkby Player for Brentford|publisher=Sheffield Daily Telegraph|date=6 May 1912|page=1}}</ref> at least as early as 1907<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham County Versus Doncaster Rovers|publisher=Sheffield Daily Telegraph|date=27 December 1907|page=9}}</ref> who were regulars in the FA Cup at that time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham County Fined|publisher=Sheffield Daily Telegraph|date=23 March 1907|page=11}}</ref> He next joined South Kirkby<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=South Kirkby Colliery (Almost) Complete History|url=http://www.southkirkbycolliery.co.uk/player-a-z|publisher=Matthew Thomas|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> then joined Brentford in 1912.<ref>{{cite news|title=Football Fancies|publisher=Star Green 'Un|date=1 February 1913|page=1}}</ref> In the [[1912\u201313 Brentford F.C. season|1912-1913 season]] he made 8 appearances for Brentford and in the [[1913\u201314 Brentford F.C. season|1913-1914 season]] he made 7 appearances. In total he made 15 appearances for Brentford. After World War One, Tommy Fells is known to have returned to South Kirkby Colliery in 1919.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|