{"title_page": "Eva (2018 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Eva\n| image          = Eva (2018 film).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Beno\u00eet Jacquot]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* M\u00e9lita Toscan du Plantier\n* Marie-Jeanne Pascal\n* Olivier P\u00e8re\n}}\n| screenplay     = Beno\u00eet Jacquot\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Eve (James Hadley Chase novel)|Eve]]''|[[James Hadley Chase]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Isabelle Huppert]]\n* [[Gaspard Ulliel]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Bruno Coulais]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = Julia Gregory\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Arte France Cin\u00e9ma\n* [[EuropaCorp]]\n* Macassar Productions\n}}\n| distributor    = [[EuropaCorp Distribution]]\n| released       = {{film date|2018|02|17|[[68th Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin]]|2018|03|07|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 102 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| gross          = $1,184,348<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt6414890/|title=Eva|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Eva''''' is a 2018 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Beno\u00eet Jacquot]], starring [[Isabelle Huppert]] and [[Gaspard Ulliel]]. It is based on the novel ''[[Eve (James Hadley Chase novel)|Eve]]'' by [[James Hadley Chase]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/article/fichearticle_gen_carticle=18658365.html|title=Isabelle Huppert et Gaspard Ulliel dans un remake d'Eva pour Benoit Jacquot|language=fr|work=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|publisher=Webedia|date=2 December 2016|first=Brigitte|last=Baronnet|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> It was selected to compete for the [[Golden Bear]] in the main competition section at the [[68th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/berlin-film-festival-gus-van-sant-dont-worry-competition-titles-1202643615/|title=Gus Van Sant's 'Don't Worry' Among First Berlinale Competition Titles to Be Unveiled|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first=Stewart|last=Clarke|date=18 December 2017|accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/2018/08_pressemitteilungen_2018/08_pressemitteilungen_2018detail_39572.html|title=Berlinale 2018: Benoit Jacquot, Gus Van Sant, Alexey German Jr., Ma\u0142gorzata Szumowska, Philip Gr\u00f6ning, Thomas Stuber, and Laura Bispuri in the Competition / Isabel Coixet and Lars Kraume in the Berlinale Special|work=Annual Archives: 2018|publisher=[[Berlin International Film Festival]]|author=Press Office|date=18 December 2017|accessdate=22 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630000240/https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/2018/08_pressemitteilungen_2018/08_pressemitteilungen_2018detail_39572.html|archivedate=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA gigolo Bertrand steals a manuscript from a dying client and achieves success as a playwright. He resides in Paris with his fianc\u00e9 Caroline. A theatrical producer R\u00e9gis is waiting for Bertrand's follow-up play. Bertrand encounters a prostitute Eva.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Isabelle Huppert]] as Eva\n* [[Gaspard Ulliel]] as Bertrand Valade\n* [[Julia Roy]] as Caroline\n* [[Richard Berry (actor)|Richard Berry]] as R\u00e9gis\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere in the Competition section at the [[68th Berlin International Film Festival]] on 17 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/archive/jahresarchive/2018/02_programm_2018/02_filmdatenblatt_2018_201812383.html|title=Eva|work=[[Berlin International Film Festival]]|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2018/02/18/68th-berlinale-hits-misses/|title=68th Berlinale hits & misses|work=[[Boston Herald]]|first=Stephen|last=Schaefer|date=18 February 2018|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> It was released in France on 7 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=252200.html|title=Eva|work=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|language=fr|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 17%, based on 6 reviews, and an average rating of 5.1/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/eva_2018|title=Eva (2018)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating to reviews, the film has a weighted average score of 38 out of 100, based on 5 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/eva-2018|title=Eva|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nDavid Ehrlich of ''[[IndieWire]]'' gave the film a grade of C\u2212, writing: \"Stuck between a high-class thriller and a trashy Cinemax wank, Beno\u00eet Jacquot's latest feature ultimately offers the pleasures of neither.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/02/eva-review-benoit-jacquot-isabelle-huppert-1201930011/|title='Eva' Review: Not Even Isabelle Huppert Playing an Irritated Prostitute Can Save this Limp Melodrama \u2014 Berlinale 2018|work=[[IndieWire]]|first=David|last=Ehrlich|date=18 February 2018|accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> Jordan Mintzer of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote, \"''Eva'' slides off the rails during a denouement that goes full on B-movie without much credibility.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/eva-review-1077296|title='Eva': Film Review {{!}} Berlin 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Jordan|last=Mintzer|date=17 February 2018|accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Eva (1962 film)|''Eva'' (1962 film)]], an earlier adaptation of the same novel\n\n